            <commentid>24947</commentid>
            <who name="Tristan Koch">tristan.koch</who>
            <bug_when>2011-06-07 09:54:11 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>Browsers supporting the CORS extensions of XmlHttpRequest already allow cross-origin request. IE &gt;=8 offers the host object XDomainRequest that somewhat implements CORS. Evaluate if XDomainRequest can be used instead of XmlHttpRequest. It should be noted that the interface of XDomainRequest considerably differs from XmlHttpRequest.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
          <long_desc isprivate="0">
            <commentid>33601</commentid>
            <who name="Richard Sternagel">richard.sternagel</who>
            <bug_when>2013-08-08 19:01:47 +0200</bug_when>
            <thetext>On February 10, 2012 the IE team announced [1] that IE 10 is supporting Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) for XMLHttpRequest (XHR). That means we speak of special treatment for IE 8-9 only while IE 10+ support the standard compliant way of CORS out of the box. IMO that qualifies this bug for &quot;WONTFIX&quot;.

[1] http://blogs.msdn.com/b/ie/archive/2012/02/09/cors-for-xhr-in-ie10.aspx</thetext>
          </long_desc>
      
      

